    <stitle>Body Builder Electrical Data Book - SINGLE REDUCTION AXLES: SPICER S100-S, S105-S, S135-S, S150-S - REMOVE -
        PINION
    </stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="remove" graphiccount="3">
        <title>PINION</title>
        <para>Refer to
            <hotlnk xrefid="f1401707">Figure 7</hotlnk>.
        </para>
        <figure id="f1401707" figsize="pg-wide">
            <graphic id="g1401707" filename="../figg14/G1401707.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="514px"
                     scalefitheight="272px"/>
            <caption>Figure 7. Pinion Exploded View</caption>
        </figure>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove yoke nut.</para>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Use of a torque multiplier is recommended as torque specification on input nut is 700 to 900
                        ft-lbs. (950 to 1,220 Nm).
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove yoke using a yoke puller service tool (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401708">Figure 8</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401708" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401708" filename="../figg14/G1401708.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 8. Remove Yoke Using Yoke Puller Service Tool</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove oil seal.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place carrier in a press with threaded end of pinion face up (
                <hotlnk xrefid="f1401709">Figure 9</hotlnk>).
            </para>
            <figure id="f1401709" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic id="g1401709" filename="../figg14/G1401709.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="272px"/>
                <caption>Figure 9. Place Carrier in Press With Threaded End of Pinion Face Up</caption>
            </figure>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Place a wood block under pinion to avoid damage to gear teeth.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Press pinion through outer bearing and out of carrier casting.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">Remove bearing preload spacer and save for use in reassembly.</para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If the gear set is to be reused, remove inner bearing at this time with a suitable puller.
                If the gear set is to be replaced, new bearings must be installed.
            </para>
        </step1>
        <step1>
            <para count="1">If bearings are to be replaced, remove bearing cups from carrier casting at this time.
            </para>
        </step1>
    </svcproc>
